# Contributing

This repo merges contributions automatically. There's no maintainer sitting
between you and the archive — a GitHub Action checks your PR and merges it
itself if it passes. Here's exactly what it checks, so your first PR is your
last PR.

## The rules

- **One file per PR.** Don't bundle multiple projects into one submission.
- **Path:** `projects/your-project-name.md` — lowercase, hyphens instead of
  spaces (e.g. `projects/night-owl-scheduler.md`).
- **Only add.** Don't edit or delete any existing file in the same PR — that
  gets auto-rejected, no exceptions, even if it's a typo fix. Open a separate
  PR for that.
- **Under 50KB.** This is a write-up, not a whitepaper. Link out to a repo or
  deck for the deep detail.
- **Max 10 links** in the file. More than that reads as link-spam to the bot
  and it'll bounce the PR.
- **Fill in every field from `TEMPLATE.md`.** The bot checks for the
  presence of: `project_name`, `team`, `hackathon`, `outcome`,
  `what_judges_saw`, `what_this_shows`.
- **New GitHub accounts:** if your account is less than 3 days old, the PR
  will be held for a manual look instead of auto-merging. This isn't
  personal — it's the one spam filter a bot can't fully automate away.

## If the bot rejects your PR

It'll comment on the PR explaining exactly which rule it failed. Fix that
one thing and push again to the same branch — the check re-runs
automatically, no need to open a new PR.

## What NOT to submit

- Marketing for a product, service, or "opportunity"
- Anything that isn't a real hackathon project you or your team built
- Duplicate entries for the same project (one entry per project, ever)
